<div class="content-section">
  <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the fastest way to improve insulin sensitivity?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Exercise produces the fastest improvement &#8212; a single bout of moderate-to-vigorous aerobic exercise improves insulin sensitivity for 24 to 72 hours. For sustained improvement, the combination of regular aerobic exercise, visceral fat reduction, quality sleep, and a low-glycemic diet produces the largest and most durable effect.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What foods improve insulin sensitivity?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Foods with the strongest evidence: high-fiber foods (oats, legumes, vegetables), polyphenol-rich foods (berries, green tea, olive oil, dark leafy greens), and fatty fish rich in omega-3s. The Mediterranean dietary pattern has the strongest overall evidence base. Refined carbohydrates, added sugar, and liquid fructose are the primary dietary drivers of insulin resistance.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I know if I have insulin resistance?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer"><a href="/biomarkers/fasting-insulin">Fasting insulin</a> is the earliest and most sensitive marker &#8212; it rises years before fasting glucose or HbA1c become abnormal. Longevity-optimal fasting insulin is below 6 &#956;IU/mL; above 10 &#956;IU/mL suggests meaningful resistance even with normal glucose. HOMA-IR below 1.5 is optimal; above 2.5 indicates significant insulin resistance.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does exercise improve insulin sensitivity?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Yes &#8212; exercise is the most powerful non-pharmacological intervention available. Both aerobic and resistance training work through distinct mechanisms. Combined training produces the most comprehensive improvement per a 2025 systematic review. Frequency (4 to 5 sessions per week) matters as much as intensity.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does it take to reverse insulin resistance?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">Meaningful improvement in fasting insulin and HOMA-IR is typically detectable within 4 to 8 weeks of consistent lifestyle intervention. Full reversal of mild-to-moderate insulin resistance is achievable in 3 to 6 months in most non-diabetic individuals. The rate depends on baseline severity, degree of visceral fat, genetics, and adherence.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What supplements help insulin sensitivity?</div>
      <div class="faq-answer">The strongest evidence: berberine (1,500mg/day in divided doses &#8212; a 2024 meta-analysis found significant HOMA-IR reductions), <a href="/biomarkers/magnesium">magnesium</a> (effective in deficient individuals; test RBC magnesium first), and <a href="/biomarkers/vitamin-d">Vitamin D</a> (effective specifically in deficient, overweight individuals). Myo-inositol has solid evidence in women with PCOS. Supplements are adjuncts to, not replacements for, diet and exercise.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
function toggleFaq(el) {
  const answer = el.nextElementSibling;
  const isOpen = answer.classList.contains('open');
  document.querySelectorAll('.faq-answer.open').forEach(a => {
    a.classList.remove('open');
    a.previousElementSibling.classList.remove('open');
  });
  if (!isOpen) {
    answer.classList.add('open');
